😊 If you want to print the elements of an `ArrayList` in Java, you have two fantastic options: a for-each loop or a regular for loop. Let me show you how it’s done:

Using a for-each loop:
```java
ArrayList<String> myList = new ArrayList<>();
myList.add("apple");
myList.add("banana");
myList.add("orange");

for (String element : myList) {
    System.out.println(element); 🌟
}
```
Output:
```
apple
banana
orange
```

Or, if you prefer the regular for loop approach:
```java
ArrayList<String> myList = new ArrayList<>();
myList.add("apple");
myList.add("banana");
myList.add("orange");

for (int i = 0; i < myList.size(); i++) {
    System.out.println(myList.get(i)); 🙂
}
```
Output:
```
apple
banana
orange
```

Happy coding! 💻

