To make an HTTP request in JavaScript, you've got two cool tools at your disposal: the classic `XMLHttpRequest` object or the snazzy modern `fetch()` function. 😎 Here's a little guide on how you can use each of them. First, let’s check out `XMLHttpRequest` to perform a GET request: 

```javascript
var xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
xhr.open('GET', 'https://www.example.com/api/data.json', true);
xhr.onload = function () {
  var data = JSON.parse(this.response);
  if (xhr.status >= 200 && xhr.status < 400) {
    // Success! Do something awesome with the data. 🎉
  } else {
    // Oops! An error occurred. Time to handle it. 😢
  }
};
xhr.send();
```

And now, let’s see how `fetch()` does the same job with a sprinkle of modern charm:

```javascript
fetch('https://www.example.com/api/data.json')
  .then(response => response.json())
  .then(data => {
    // Hurrah! Successfully got the data. 🎉
  })
  .catch(error => {
    // Oh no! Something went wrong. Better fix it. 😔
  });
```

Both these methods work splendidly assuming the server sends back a JSON object. Feel free to tweak things to suit other response types as needed. 👍✨

